The 46-year-old from Melbourne said he and his partner James are waiting to see if they can bring their baby boy Rhyley home.

He explained that the Australian couples he had spoken to thought they would be in Thailand for five or six weeks and 'now there are rumours they will have to stay three months or six months, or who knows how long'.

He said many are experiencing financial difficulties.

A recent statement from the Australian Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade, regarding Australian parents being prevented from bringing their children home from Thailand, said: 'We have been advised that Thai authorities may enforce enhanced documentation requirements when exiting the country, when they suspect a child has been born by surrogacy in Thailand.

